dismissalText.long: c KC Brathwaite b CR Brathwaite
dismissalText.commentary: Sikandar Raza c KC Brathwaite b CR Brathwaite 77 (81b 7x4 0x6 103m) SR: 95.06

dismissalComment.html: taken at long-off. Lovely shot but with the fielder there, it was always fraught with risk. Quite full outside off, Raza opens the face and lofts the ball with the full face of the bat. Goes very high, more elevation than distance. Kraigg Brathwaite moves across to his left, eyes on the ball at all times, and takes a good catch near his chest, juggled but job done. Superb knock from Raza

headshotImage.longCaption: Brian Chari player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: oh what a catch. Sensational stuff from Holder. The best catch I've seen this year. Wow. A full delivery on off and middle, the pressure on Chari was too much. He gets forward and heaves the ball in the air into the leg side. Holder hurtles back after it from short midwicket. Deep square leg is running in as well for the catch. He keeps an eye on both somehow. Keeps running back, and even as square leg is coming close to him, he keeps his eye on the ball and completes a stunning catch with both hands in front of him, diving to the ground as ball makes contact with his hands. Throws the ball up nonchalantly. More skill in these catches than reflex ones, meaning the difficulty level rises multi-fold.

dismissalText.commentary: Chamu Chibhabha run out (†Hope/CR Brathwaite) 25 (33b 4x4 0x6 56m) SR: 75.75

dismissalComment.html: oh no. What a way to go. After all the hardwork. Chamu is run-out. A good length delivery outside off, dabbed towards the keeper. Chari is ball-watching and yells "noo", but with his back to Chamu. Could Chamu have not heard him because there was no eye contact. Chamu carries on, Chari doesn't leave. The keeper picks up and lobs the ball back to the bowler who runs Chamu out. That is not good from Chari. Has to look at his partner either way, if it is a run or not

Rovman Powell at backward point runs across a long way and puts in the dive to take an extremely tough catch

commentTextItems.html: unbelievable scenes at Queens. What a match! Zimbabwe are leaping in joy an why wouldn't they! This has been a remarkable fightback. But let's not forget to give credit to the bowler. What a superb delivery under pressure. Fires it very full and outside off, just around the line forcing the batsman to reach out. Holder can't make contact but Carter sets off for the run from the non-striker's end. The wicketkeeper has a shy at the stumps and Carter is caught short. An inch outside and it could have been a wide. A perfect last delivery and full marks to Tiripano

commentPostTextItems.html: Little doubt that several hearts at Queens must have raced as fast as Zimbabwe's over-rate. At the end of it all, we have just the second tie of the year. There was a kind of symmetry to both innings. Like Zimbabwe, West Indies lost two early wickets. Both innings had a big third-wicket partnership, before a flurry of wickets pegged them back. In hindsight, that Carlos Brathwaite shot with three needed off five was probably the turning point. But one would assume that a big-hitter like him would back his strength. Unfortunately for West Indies, it didn't come off. Zimbabwe face Sri Lanka next and a win in that match will take them up to second. Hope to see you then. That's it from us on this thrilling Saturday evening. Cheers!
Tarun: "Do both teams get 2 points for this match ?" That's right.
Hope: The hundred does not mean much if you don't win. Credit must go to their bowlers. It was about winning the game, unfortunately, we could not do it.
Shai Hope is the Man of the Match for his century.

Jason Holder: Mixed emotions. We should have won the game, but that's cricket. It's important for the guys to learn from this game and make sure it does not happen in fututre. We had a few positives in the game. Shai batted outstandingly and the bowlers did a superb job.

Graeme Cremer: We made some mistakes in the second half, but the fight we showed there was incredible, full credit to the boys. We were a bit sloppy on the field, dropped a couple of catches, but hopefully, we can take the positives from this match into the next match. Craig and Raza batted superbly. We thought we fell 15-20 runs short, but credit to the boys for the fight they showed.
First up, umpire Russell Tiffin is being felicitated for his 150th ODI match. He is honoured by ZC.
What a heart-rattling match. We will have the presentations with you shortly.
Neel: "Do we have a super over now??" I'm afraid not.
Ahmad: "Donald trump and donald tiripano...what a month.."
Dan: "Woooooooww!!! What a match! Love it"
Ruchir: "Wow what a match this has been, people watching IndvEng and NZvPak, should follow this series as well"

dismissalText.commentary: Brian Chari c Holder b CR Brathwaite 15 (41b 1x4 0x6 65m) SR: 36.58

dismissalComment.html: oh what a catch. Sensational stuff from Holder. The best catch I've seen this year. Wow. A full delivery on off and middle, the pressure on Chari was too much. He gets forward and heaves the ball in the air into the leg side. Holder hurtles back after it from short midwicket. Deep square leg is running in as well for the catch. He keeps an eye on both somehow. Keeps running back, and even as square leg is coming close to him, he keeps his eye on the ball and completes a stunning catch with both hands in front of him, diving to the ground as ball makes contact with his hands. Throws the ball up nonchalantly. More skill in these catches than reflex ones, meaning the difficulty level rises multi-fold.

dismissalText.commentary: Johnson Charles lbw b Tiripano 19 (21b 1x4 1x6 31m) SR: 90.47

dismissalComment.html: that is a lot closer and given by umpire Tiffin. Charles wants the review. An offcutter that pitches outside off, that has come back some way and struck Charles in front of middle and leg. No bat on that. The only question is if it is missing the stumps entirely. Not a terrible review. But He'll have to go because the ball is just about clipping leg stump. A good knock but beaten by the slowness this time. Just missed a flick

dismissalText.commentary: Evin Lewis c Chibhabha b Cremer 18 (17b 4x4 0x6 20m) SR: 105.88

dismissalComment.html: oh, dear! What has Lewis done here. It was a loosener from Cremer, short and spinning in slightly. Right in the slot for Lewis to dispatch it out of the ground. He sets himself up and gets in position early before nailing a muscular pull. But out of all the vast ares in the leg side field, he picks out deep square leg and sends it straight down his throat as Chibhabha latches on to it just before the boundary. Didn't have to move an inch

dismissalText.commentary: Kraigg Brathwaite c Ervine b Williams 78 (117b 2x4 0x6 174m) SR: 66.66

dismissalComment.html: and Brathwaite's stubborn resistance comes to an end. He comes down the track and looks to go over long-off. But the ball isn't quite full enough and he does not get to the pitch of it. Lofts it straight down after making room but doesn't get it off the middle and hits it straight down the throat of long-off who snaffles it without discomfort. Everybody at the ground rejoices. Could there be a late twist to this?

dismissalText.commentary: Jonathan Carter run out (†Moor) 1 (1b 0x4 0x6 4m) SR: 100

dismissalComment.html: unbelievable scenes at Queens. What a match! Zimbabwe are leaping in joy an why wouldn't they! This has been a remarkable fightback. But let's not forget to give credit to the bowler. What a superb delivery under pressure. Fires it very full and outside off, just around the line forcing the batsman to reach out. Holder can't make contact but Carter sets off for the run from the non-striker's end. The wicketkeeper has a shy at the stumps and Carter is caught short. An inch outside and it could have been a wide. A perfect last delivery and full marks to Tiripano
